  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Frameworks and Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- International monetary regulations\n- Global standards for combating financial crimes\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Information sharing agreements\n- Extradition protocols\n- Joint investigative efforts\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Cross-border financial transparency requirements\n\n4. Enforcement Coordination\n- International law enforcement collaboration\n- Interpol and other transnational investigative networks\n- Coordinated financial investigations\n- Sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n\n5. Standardization of Legal Approaches\n- Harmonizing definitions of money laundering\n- Developing consistent legal frameworks\n- Creating common investigative and prosecutorial standards\n\n6. Technological Collaboration\n- Shared digital platforms for tracking financial transactions\n- Advanced data analysis and monitoring systems\n- Blockchain and cryptocurrency tracking mechanisms\n\nThese intersections create complex, multi-layered approaches to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
